✨ Hard work looks slow from the inside — but turning an idea into research, and research into something worthy of an IEEE stage, makes it all make sense.

Our research reached an important stage recently as we had the opportunity to present our paper at the IEEE International Conference on Future Technologies (ICFT 2025) 🎙️. Our paper titled “Biodegradable and Non-biodegradable Waste Classification for Smart Waste Management” was presented on 7th & 8th November 2025 🗓️ at an event organized by Walchand College of Engineering(A Govt. Aided Autonomous Institute),SANGLI-M.S 🏛️ and technically sponsored by the IEEE Maharashtra Section 🔌.

This wasn’t just a project being showcased — it was a journey that pushed us to learn, unlearn and stay consistent alongside academics and another ongoing major project. What began early this year as a small experiment gradually grew into something strong enough to reach a conference stage 💡.

We realized early that the biggest challenge wasn’t deep learning — it was data. While non-biodegradable waste datasets existed online, biodegradable waste images were limited. So we built that dataset ourselves 🧪 — storing items for days, capturing images through changing lighting & weather, and documenting their gradual degradation. It was slow, but it made our dataset real 📸.

Annotation came next — and anyone who has annotated hundreds of images knows that grind 😮‍💨. Late nights labeling and correcting mistakes, while continuously expanding the dataset with additional external images to maintain balance and diversity.

Once the dataset became reliable, we moved on to training and hyperparameter tuning multiple deep learning models ⚙️ until their performance aligned with real-world behavior instead of just validation scores.

Then came the most underestimated phase — writing the research paper ✍️. Literature surveys, restructuring sections, formatting and refining draft after draft taught us as much as the technical work itself.

Balancing this research with semester workload, continuous submissions and another project wasn’t easy — but slow consistency made it possible 🔁.

None of this would have reached ICFT without the support and guidance of Ms. Aditi Pawde Ma’am 🌟. From dataset decisions to modelling direction to paper structure, her mentorship shaped every stage of the work.

Grateful to have worked with my teammates Suyash Yadav & Purva Markam — this journey happened because we pushed together through every phase 🤝.

👉 This project reinforced something important: doing things properly takes patience and discipline — and it's always worth it.

